<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-675-542  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 675 542.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Sept 18 1989 n435 p50(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC's golden deal. (early retirement) (Street Talk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sperling, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In an attempt to enforce its no-layoff policy in the face ofslumping sales in the minicomputer market, DEC is offering itsmanufacturing employees severance settlements in exchange fortheir resignation.andP;  This is the third time in four years that DEChas offered its manufacturing employees incentives to leave.andO;Slumping hardware sales affect the number of systems that aremanufactured, and it also takes fewer people to make computersthan it did five years ago.andP;  Manufacturing is overloaded withpeople, while the sales department is understaffed.andP;  The severancepackage includes 40 weeks' pay for those employed at least twoyears, 64 weeks' pay for those with 11 to 20 years' experience,and four weeks' additional pay for each year beyond 20.andP;  Those whochoose to accept the package receive benefits for one year andaccelerated restricted stock options.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (personnel management).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     Personnel ManagementReductionManufacturingFinancial Stability.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>